		   <span class="sm">Posted: Tue, Oct 19th 2:38 AM 2004 EST</span><span class="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/db/classes.html?class=12&mid=100506681140812&num=15;post=1;replyto=1098167894285346122"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a>    <a name="1098167894285346122"></a></span></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" class="mform2" ><span class="fs8"><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=73372"><span class="Sage">The One and Only Malaclypse</span></a><b><span class="Sage"><br/>Sage</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />207 posts
		   <br /><span class="nobr"><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Good  </span><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist;addname=Malaclypse;type=Address" class="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book" /> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1" alt=""/></span></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%">
<p>K, again here's the breakdown. Earth does work well for soloing, but it is not the be all or end all. Pre lvl 51 the fire pet works as well or better. <br /> <br />Pre 51 the pets are fairly balanced. They all have their advantages and disadvantages. <br /> <br />Earth: pre lvl 51 earth makes a decent tank and also roots. However rooting a mob prevents it from doing the whole death walk thing, meaning it gets hit more, meaning you have to heal more. This can be an advantage if you're damage shielding your pet, but can also be a pain. It also is almost never used in groups because it throws off any other rooting classes there and also signifigantly lowers the damage rangers can do to a mob. <br /> <br />lvl 51 and above earth has a lot of the same problems, and all of the same advantages. The HP that the earth pet has can actually make it a fairly decent tank for a group, particularly with the lvl 65 Rathe's Son and the OoW version. The reason earth pets work well for soloing is because you don't have to worry about aggro (unless you're fighting something that summons) due to the root. The root factor also makes it fairly easy to chain pets at a mob until either it dies or you run out of mana. Earth pets have very high AC and damage mitigation IE, getting hit for less than full damage. <br /> <br /> <br />Air: Air has several substantal advantages, but several disadvantages. Air stuns mobs. Lots. This is good if you're fighting a caster and can help reduce damage to a tank if you're fighting anything else. Downside is that the stun has a push factor to it, in other words an air pet will slowly push a mob backwards which can be a real problem if you don't have a lot of room to fight. The air pet also has a very substantial level of damage avoidance IE, dodging incoming hits, meaning that it makes an excellent tank. These attributes remain constant through all of the air pets. <br /> <br />Water: Water has excellent HP regeneration and also a pretty good ice based proc/nuke that it uses fairly regularly. Sort of a mix between air and earth. Useful in groups when you don't want the push of an air pet, or the rooting of an earth pet. Water and fire pets have higher damage per second than air and earth pre 51. <br /> <br />Post 51 it becomes one of the best DPS pets we have. The 62 version is only slightly surpased by our 1.0 epic pet, and only then on mobs at or below lvl 61 (62 if you're using a pet focus). <br /> <br />Fire: The fire pet matches DPS with the water pet pre 51. It also has an innate damage shield that is superior to all of ours up to lvl 51+ pets. Meaning it makes a great tank against quick hitting mobs that don't have a lot of HP, or against swarms of green stuff. Pre 51, this is THE pet to farm with. It also can tank fairly well, but has relatively low HP. <br /> <br />Post 51 things get wierd. The fire pet turns into a wizard. For an example, picture inviting a lower level wizard into your party. Picture that lower level wizard then snorting a few lines of cocaine, hitting himself in the head with a claw hammer a few times and then casting random spells at a mob until you get sick of it and kill him in his sleep. This gives you a general idea of the post 51 fire pets. They're not totally useless, just bloody close to it. There may be some secret special use for this pet, but most mages hate it so damn much that no one has bothered to really research it. Get it anyway. <br /> <br />We also get a few odd pets such as the monster summoning line, which is good fun, but basically an earth/water clone, and Dyzil's Deafening Decoy which is a lvl 56 version of the pre 51 fire pets + a pretty massive taunt. <br /> <br />Now, which of the pets is best? None of em. They all have their uses. NEVER just stick with one pet, because then you are an idjet, and you neglect about half of the things a mage is capable of. Use them all, figure out when to use each. If you use the wrong pet at the wrong time, you will die where you might have lived if you're soloing or your friendly group mates will be glad to smack you one upside the head if your grouping. <br /> <br />And EVEN AFTER GETTING AN UPGRADED PET, KEEP THE OLD ONE. I can not stress this enough. NEVER delete a spell, EVER. Get them ALL. You never know when you will discover a new use for something. And I will assure you right now, you can pull some jaw dropping tricks with lower level pets even at 66+. It's up to you to figure out what they are. <br /> <br /> <br />Lord Faelawen Starfyre, the Legendary Mad Mage of Povar, Arch Nemesis of the Evil Squirrel Empire, Advocate of RasCals.</p>
